<li id="cite_note-43"><b><a href="#cite_ref-43" title="">^</a></b> For translation of <i>deva</i> in singular noun form as "a deity, god", and in plural form as "the gods" or "the heavenly or shining ones", see: <a href="#CITEREFMonier-Williams2001" title="">Monier-Williams 2001</a>, p.&#160;492. In fact, there are different ranks among the devas. The highest are the immortal <a href="/wiki/Mahadeva" title="Mahadeva">Mahadevas</a>, such as Shiva, Vishnu, etc. The second-rank devas, such as Ganesha, are described as their offspring: they are "born", and their "lifespan" is quite limited. In ISKCON the word is translated as "demigods", although it can also denote such heavenly denizens as <a href="/wiki/Gandharva" title="Gandharva">gandharvas</a>. See: <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://www.veda.harekrsna.cz/planetarium/index.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.veda.harekrsna.cz/planetarium/index.htm" rel="nofollow">"Vedic cosmology"</a>. <i>Vedic Knowledge Online</i>. VEDA - Bhaktivedanta Book Trust<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.veda.harekrsna.cz/planetarium/index.htm" class="external free" title="http://www.veda.harekrsna.cz/planetarium/index.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.veda.harekrsna.cz/planetarium/index.htm</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-06-25</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Vedic+cosmology&amp;rft.atitle=Vedic+Knowledge+Online&amp;rft.pub=VEDA+-+Bhaktivedanta+Book+Trust&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.veda.harekrsna.cz%2Fplanetarium%2Findex.htm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Hinduism"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span>. For translation of <i><span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">devatā</span></i> as "godhead, divinity", see: <a href="#CITEREFMonier-Williams2001" title="">Monier-Williams 2001</a>, p.&#160;495.</li>
